1578
01:56:20,100 --> 01:56:28,883
When the government increases taxes, it ultimately takes money away from individuals who could spend or invest it more efficiently.

1579
01:56:29,443 --> 01:56:31,004
This is a fundamental principle.

1580
01:56:31,564 --> 01:56:36,206
Individuals can make better decisions with their money than a central authority can.

1581
01:56:36,986 --> 01:56:40,087
First, consider the impact on property owners.

1582
01:56:40,707 --> 01:56:49,571
Higher taxes could drive people away, particularly those on fixed incomes or with limited means, reducing the overall attractiveness of the city.

1583
01:56:50,899 --> 01:56:58,842
This can lead to reduction in property values and a smaller tax base over time, the very opposite of what the government hopes to achieve.

1584
01:56:59,743 --> 01:57:06,926
Second, the argument is often made that projects such as new schools and infrastructure are essential for public welfare.

1585
01:57:07,386 --> 01:57:12,889
This is true, but one must ask whether raising taxes is the optimal solution.

1586
01:57:13,829 --> 01:57:28,583
Alternative methods such as public-private partnerships, leveraging private investments, and utilizing existing resources more effectively might achieve the same goals without imposing higher taxes on residents.

1587
01:57:29,571 --> 01:57:33,195
The core issue here is one of economic freedom and efficiency.

1588
01:57:33,955 --> 01:57:41,403
By significantly raising real estate taxes, the government imposes a burden on its residents and potentially stifles economic activity.

1589
01:57:42,043 --> 01:57:46,908
There's no assurance that the benefits of any infrastructure projects will outweigh these costs.

1590
01:57:47,589 --> 01:57:53,115
Therefore, the government should consider more innovative and less burdensome ways to fund these initiatives.

1591
01:57:54,491 --> 01:58:02,376
Some alternatives that the city government should consider instead of raising real estate taxes are one, economic growth.

1592
01:58:03,137 --> 01:58:11,282
Implement a multifaceted campaign to stimulate economic growth, thereby expanding the tax base and increasing overall revenue.

1593
01:58:11,783 --> 01:58:14,385
Two, public-private partnerships.

1594
01:58:14,965 --> 01:58:22,250
Collaborate with private companies to fund and manage infrastructure projects, sharing both risks and benefits.

1595
01:58:22,890 --> 01:58:23,050
Three,

1596
01:58:24,332 --> 01:58:24,932
User fees.

1597
01:58:25,693 --> 01:58:38,078
Introduce or increase fees for specific services, such as water and sewer, waste management, parking, or recreational facilities, ensuring that users directly pay for the services they consume.

1598
01:58:40,319 --> 01:58:48,721
Municipal bonds, issue bonds to raise capital for infrastructure projects, spreading the cost over time and across current and future beneficiaries.

1599
01:58:49,421 --> 01:58:59,284
Five, prioritizing spending, reallocate funds from less critical areas, tightening the budget can free up resources to pay for infrastructure projects.

1600
01:58:59,904 --> 01:59:07,627
Six, improving efficiency, streamline government operations to cut costs, reallocating savings to our infrastructure needs.

1601
01:59:08,108 --> 01:59:17,111
Seven, selling city assets, evaluate and sell underutilized public assets, such as land or buildings to generate revenue.

1602
01:59:18,892 --> 01:59:24,477
lease revenues, lease public assets, or increase their efficiency to generate additional income streams.

1603
01:59:25,238 --> 01:59:34,026
The message just described can mitigate the need for a Proposition 2.5 override in order to maintain and enhance city infrastructure and services.

